ce:section.ce:para:
The fluorescence property of the nanohybrid was further explored to study the presence of As (III) in water (Fig. 5
                        ). The nitrogen and oxygen atoms present in the nanohybrids act as the main sites for adsorption for the metal ions because they can easily donate their electrons. The ionic radius of As (III) is much higher compared to nitrogen and oxygen and hence, its electron cloud can be easily deformed by the labile electrons of nitrogen and oxygen present in the nanohybrid [34,36]. However, among all the three nanohybrids PNCD 3 detected As (III) more efficiently, (shown in Fig. 5 (c)), compared to PNCD 1 and PNCD 2 (Fig. 5(a) and (b)). This is because of the fact that the proportion of CD in PNCD 3 is more and hence, the surface functionalized groups are more which result in more effective interaction with the metal ions compared to PNCD 1 and PNCD 2. This also accounts for the less fluctuations of the onset values in PNCD 3 compared to PNCD 1 and 2 since PN is less stable in solution compared to CD. The nanohybrids demonstrate the enhancement of fluorescence on increasing the concentration of As (III) from 0.001 ppb to 2.000 ppb. An enhancement of about 9.2 folds was measured as the concentration approaches to 2.000 ppb. The ratio of emission intensities of the nanohybrid with (F) to without As (III) (Fo) was calculated and plotted against corresponding concentration of the samples (Fig. 6
                        ). As shown in this figure, the best range of concentration of As (III) in linear response is from 0.05 to 1.5 ppb with a correlation coefficient, R = 0.977. The limit of detection (LOD) is about 0.677 ppb and the limit of quantification is 2.052 which is based on the standard deviation (σ) and the slope of the calibration curve (S) according to the formula: LOD = 3.3 (σ/S). However, experimentally As (III) was detected as low as 0.001 ppb. This signifies that the PNCD 3 nanohybrid can effectively detect the presence of As (III) even at very low concentration. The lowest concentration of As (III) was determined by using this nanohybrid is lower than the lowest concentration of As (1.0 ppb) determined by Gumpu et al. and Kallurie et al. [37,38]. Most importantly, the experimentally determined lowest concentration of As (III) is more accurate than the theoretically obtained LOD value, because the theoretical evaluation of data basically results in two types of errors, namely, random errors (precision) and systematic errors (bias). Therefore, any evaluation dropping below the theoretically calculated limit or zero may result into incorrect estimation. So, the actual concentration observed experimentally should only be considered even if they fall below the theoretically calculated LOD value as stated by Analytical Methods Committee [39]. The control studies were also performed using PN and CD at different concentrations of As (III) (Fig. 6 (a) and 6 (b)). The results showed that the PNCD was more efficient compared to CD and PN. This is due to n–π* transition of CO bond by means of delocalisation of π electrons. Moreover, the combination of CD and PN acts as an effective donor-acceptor pair which results into efficient energy transfer system in PNCD [13,20]. The effectiveness of fluorimetric detection of PNCD 3 for 2.000 ppb of As (III) was also checked in different buffer solutions of pH in the range of 1.6–7.4 (Fig. 6(c)). The study revealed that the decrease in the pH of the medium caused quenching of the fluorescence intensity. This variation is mainly due to the change of the oxidation states of the polymeric chain of PN from stable emeraldine base (EB) form to the acidic emeraldine salt (ES) form which has more positive electron accepting sites. Therefore, the conjugation between CD and PN increases and the intensity decreases. However, as the pH of the medium increases the transformation of ES to EB takes place which decreases the conjugation effect and therefore, the effectiveness of energy transfer from CD to PN decreases. As a result, the fluorescence intensity increases since the number of free electrons increases and therefore effective electrostatic interaction with As (III) takes place [20,33].
